g.text: Desing consisteng hashing
TO achive horizontal scaling, it is important to distribute
request/data efficiently and evenly across servers.
The rehasing problem
If you have n cache servers, a common way to hash is
serverIndex = hash(key) % N, where N is the size
of the server pool
this approach works well when the size of the server pool
is fixed and data distribution is even, problems arise when
servers are added
Consistent hashing
Is a special kind of hashing such that when a hash table
is re-sized and consistent hashing is used only k/n keys
need to be remapped on average.
Hash space and hash ring
Assume, SHA-1 is used as the hash function f, and the output
range of the hash function is x0,x1,x2,x3...xn. In crytography
SHA-1 hash space goes from 0 to 2^160 - 1.
By connecting both ends we get a hash ring as shown
Hash servers
Each server gets an ID (usually its IP or name) and we
run it through the same hash function.
hash("ServerA") 10
hash("ServerB") 40
hash("ServerC") 70
A B C
Place data (keys) on the ring
Now we take the key (like a username or file ID) and hash
it too.
hash("apple") 15
hash("banana") 50
hash("cherry") 90
Assign keys to servers
A key belongs to the first server clockwise from its
position.
On the ring:
"apple" (15) first server clockwise is B(40)
"banana" (50) first server clockwise is C(70)
"cherry" (90) wraps around first server clockwise is A(10)
The consisten hashing algorithm was introduced by Karger et al
at MIT
The basic steps are:
- Map servers and keys on to the ring using uniformly
distributed hash funciton
- To find out which server a key is mapped to, go clockwise
from the key position until the first server on the ring is found
Problems
Two problems identified.
It is impossible to keep the same size of partitions on the ring
for all the servers considering a server can be added or removed.
A partition is the hash space between adjacet servers.
Second, it is possible to have non-uniform key distribution on the
ring.
Unequal partition sizes unequal workload distribution.
Non-uniform key placement hotspots and uneven usage of resources.
Virtual nodes (vnodes): Assign multiple positions per physical server to smooth
out partition sizes.
Good hash functions: Spread keys uniformly across the ring.
Dynamic load balancing: Reassign partitions proactively when imbalance is
detected.
Find affected keys
When you add or remove a server in consistent hashing, only the keys in one
specific section of the ring move.
Adding a server
Find the server that will be just before the new one on the ring (the
predecessor).
All keys whose hash is after the predecessor and up to the new servers position
now belong to the new server.
Those are the affected keys.
Removing a server
Find the server just before the one being removed (the predecessor).
All keys in that same range (from predecessor to the removed server) move to
the next server after the removed one.
Those are the affected keys.
What is a key?
In hashing, a key is just the identifier for some piece of data you want to store
or retrieve.
If youre building a cache: the key could be "user:1234".
If youre storing files: the key could be "photo.jpg".
If youre handling sessions: the key could be "sessionToken_abc123".
In a database: "customer_email" could be a key to look up customer data.
Why its called a key
Its like a label or name tag for the data:
You hash the key (the label) to decide
where to put the value (the actual
data) in the cluster.
In consistent hashing
We hash the key to get a number.
That number corresponds to a position on the ring.
The server at or after that position stores the data for that key.
In consistent hashing, the hash algorithm is what
takes a key (like "user:123") and turns it into a
number that can be placed on the ring.
Common choices
MD5
Old cryptographic hash (not secure anymore for crypto, but fine for distribution).
Produces 128-bit numbers good spread on the ring.
Used in early consistent hashing implementations (like memcached clients).
SHA-1 / SHA-256
Cryptographic hashes from the SHA family.
Larger output space (160/256 bits).
Slower than MD5 but also more uniform for large-scale systems.
MurmurHash
Non-cryptographic, very fast.
Excellent uniform distribution.
Widely used in distributed systems like Cassandra, Hadoop.
FNV (FowlerNollVo)
Very fast, simple.
Often used when you want low CPU usage and still decent spread.
CRC32
Short 32-bit hash from cyclic redundancy check.
Fast, but smaller space more collisions if the cluster is huge.
